5|$|December 2001: During {{the opening}} {{stages of the}} war in Afghanistan {{launched}} following the September 11 attacks, the U.S. and its allies believed that bin Laden was hiding in the rugged mountains at Tora Bora. Despite overrunning <b>the</b> <b>Taliban</b> and al-Qaeda positions, they failed to capture or kill him.|$|E
5|$|In 2008, NATO {{forces in}} southeastern Afghanistan {{deployed}} sub-company-sized patrols to the Pakistan border to disrupt supplies flowing to <b>the</b> <b>Taliban</b> from the Federally Administered Tribal Regions of Pakistan. They established small patrol bases, which came under regular attack by Taliban forces.|$|E
25|$|On May 4, 2002, Operation Torii is launched, and Lieutenant-Colonel Stogran leads an {{international}} task force, of which 400 Canadian soldiers. The {{goal of the}} mission was to discover networks of caves used by <b>the</b> <b>Talibans</b> and Al-Qaeda, {{as well as to}} gather intelligence in the Tora Bora region.|$|R
40|$|This essay {{analyzes}} the evolution, with an historical-political approach, {{of the situation}} in Afghanistan following the end of the Soviet occupation. It focuses on the rise of <b>the</b> <b>Talibans</b> movement, its tribal and religious bases {{as well as on the}} role played by other regional actors, such as Pakistan...|$|R
